In Fig. 21, the impact of Γ and Zipf parameter to average cache occupation in the UE level is evaluated in ER model. It indicates that lower α leads to more cache occupation in the UE level. Once the maximum of content copies Γ in the UE level increases, more cache resources are sliced for contents in the UE level. When the number of NUE is 60, the popularity of contents is high (α = 1.5), and the maximum of content copies Γ is equal to or more than 8 copies in the UE level, that is to say, Γ/NUE is more than 13%, no more cache occupation allocated in the UE level is required.

The impact of Γ to average cache occupation in the SBS level in ER model is shown in Fig. 22. From Fig. 22, it is visible that the parameter Γ of the UE level has little effect to the cache resources sliced in the SBS level, and high Zipf parameter α brings about less cache resource occupation in the SBS level.
Figure 23 shows the evaluation result on the impact of Γ to average cache occupation with different network models, the average cache occupation tends to nearly the same with different network models when Γ becomes great. The cache occupation is less in BA model than that in ER model because those nodes with great degree in BA model contributes more to the less average cache occupation.
